Kay! and Other Works (1926) -- tChapter Twenty-One. Strike Up the Band and Funny Face (1927) -- tChapter Twenty-Two. Rosalie and Treasure Girl (1928) -- tChapter Twenty-Three. An American in Paris (1928) and East Is West (1929) -- tChapter Twenty-Four. Show Girl and The Dybbuk (1929) -- tChapter Twenty-Five. Girl Crazy (1930) -- tChapter Twenty-Six. Delicious and the Second Rhapsody (1931) -- tChapter Twenty-Seven. Of Thee I Sing (1931) -- tChapter Twenty-Eight. George Gershwin’s Song-Book (1932) -- tChapter Twenty-Nine. The Cuban Overture (1932) and Pardon My English (1933) -- tChapter Thirty. Let ’Em Eat Cake (1933) and Variations on “I Got Rhythm” (1934) -- tChapter Thirty-One. Porgy and Bess (1935) -- tChapter Thirty-Two. The First Production of Porgy and Bess -- tChapter Thirty-Three. Porgy and Bess in Revival -- tChapter Thirty-Four. Porgy and Bess on Disc, Film, and the Concert Stage -- tChapter Thirty-Five. From Swing Is King (1936) to A Damsel in Distress (1937) -- tChapter Thirty-Six. From The Goldwyn Follies (1938) to Kiss Me, Stupid (1964) -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis comprehensive biography of George Gershwin (1898-1937) unravels the myths surrounding one of America's most celebrated composers and establishes the enduring value of his music. Gershwin created some of the most beloved music of the twentieth century and, along with Jerome Kern, Irving Berlin, and Cole Porter, helped make the golden age of Broadway golden. Howard Pollack draws from a wealth of sketches, manuscripts, letters, interviews, books, articles, recordings, films, and other materials—including a large cache of Gershwin scores discovered in a Warner Brothers warehouse in 1982—to create an expansive chronicle of Gershwin’s meteoric rise to fame. He also traces Gershwin’s powerful presence that, even today, extends from Broadway, jazz clubs, and film scores to symphony halls and opera houses.Pollack’s lively narrative describes Gershwin’s family, childhood, and education; his early career as a pianist; his friendships and romantic life; his relation to various musical trends; his writings on music; his working methods; and his tragic death at the age of 38. Unlike Kern, Berlin, and Porter, who mostly worked within the confines of Broadway and Hollywood, Gershwin actively sought to cross the boundaries between high and low, and wrote works that crossed over into a realm where art music, jazz, and Broadway met and merged. The author surveys Gershwin’s entire oeuvre, from his first surviving compositions to the melodies that his brother and principal collaborator, Ira Gershwin, lyricized after his death. Pollack concludes with an exploration of the performances and critical reception of Gershwin's music over the years, from his time to ours.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aComposerszUnited StatesvBiography. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh  aautobiography.  abiographies and memoirs.  abroadway and hollywood.  aclassical composer.  acomprehensive biography.  afamous composer.  agolden age of broadway.  ainstrumental music.  ajazz clubs.  ajazz.  amusic appreciation.  amusical trends.  aperforming arts.  apianist.  asurviving compositions.  atheater.  atragic death.  auntimely death.  awarner brothers.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052024864940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093314940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520933149423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520933149/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013 